```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "textfile.txt"; // Replace with your desired file name
    std::string searchWord = "specific"; // Replace with your desired search word

    std::ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to open " << filename << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string line;
    int count = 0;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        // Iterate through each word in the line
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(searchWord, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos += searchWord.length();
        }
    }

    std::cout << "The word \"" << searchWord << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To use this program, you need to replace the `filename` variable with the path of the text file you want to read, and the `searchWord` variable with the specific word you want to count in the file. The program reads the file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of the search word in each line. Finally, it outputs the total count.

Make sure to include necessary headers (`<iostream>`, `<fstream>`, and `<string>`) and compile the program with a C++ compiler.

